Clearly it is no Chronicle. Nor again can we include it in the class ol Annals We should have selt that it was not quite in its right place had Dr Luard comprised it in his admirable edition along with the books that come to us lrorn Dunstable‚ Tewkesbury‚ Waverley and elsewhere. Nor again can we describe it as a Cartulary. On the one hand we have not here the work os a man who year by year sets down those events, those donations, those oppressions‚ those law-suits, which affected the fortunes ol the house; and on the other hand we have nota systematis collection os documents os title, ol scoll- ments, releases and bonds, arranged according to a chrono- logical or geographical scheme. The title Liber Memo- randorum, whenever it may have been bestowed, seems aptly to describe the book that is now in our hands.
